          <avActivityHighlights>Wind slabs in the high Alpine regions.</avActivityHighlights>
          <avActivityComment>As a consequence of a gathering strong wind from westerly directions, clearly visible wind slabs will form at elevated altitudes. &lt;br/&gt; Wind slabs can be released, even by a single winter sport participant, especially on steep shady slopes in high Alpine regions, as well as on wind-loaded slopes. Caution is to be exercised at transitions into gullies and bowls. &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; In isolated cases avalanches can also be triggered in the old snowpack and reach large size. &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; As a consequence of falling temperatures, the activity of moist and wet avalanches will decrease.</avActivityComment>
          <snowpackStructureComment>In the last few days hard wind slabs formed over a wide area. The sometimes storm force wind will transport the loosely bonded old snow. In the vicinity of peaks snow depths vary greatly, depending on the infuence of the wind. &lt;br/&gt; As a consequence of a moderate wind from northwesterly directions, mostly small wind slabs will form. &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; Low and intermediate altitudes: As a consequence of falling temperatures and the strong westerly wind, a crust will form on the surface during the night. &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; High altitudes and the high Alpine regions: Weak layers exist in the old snowpack in particular on steep northwest, north and northeast facing slopes.</snowpackStructureComment>
